05764nam a22006975i 9780226608426DE-B159720210421021438.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210421t20212010ilu    fo  d z      eng d  a97802266084267 a10.7208/97802266084262doi  a(DE-B1597)575543  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ailucUS-IL 4aQH331b.B477 2010eb 7aSCI0000002bisacsh04a570.122200aBiology and Ideology from Descartes to Dawkins /cRonald L. Numbers, Denis R. Alexander. 1aChicago : bUniversity of Chicago Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (416 p.) :b30 halftones, 1 line drawing  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. The cultural authority of natural history in early modern Europe -- tChapter 2. Biology, atheism, and politics in eighteenth-century France -- tChapter 3. Eighteenth-century uses of vitalism in constructing the human sciences -- tChapter 4. Biology in the service of natural theology: Paley, Darwin, and the Bridgewater Treatises -- tchapter 5. Race, empire, and biology before Darwinism -- tChapter 6. Darwin's choice -- tChapter 7. Biology and the emergence of the Anglo-American eugenics movement -- tChapter 8. Genetics, eugenics, and the Holocaust -- tChapter 9. Darwinism, Marxism, and genetics in the Soviet Union -- tChapter 10. Evolution and the idea of social Progress -- tChapter 11. Beauty and the beast? Conceptualizing sex in evolutionary narratives -- tChapter 12. Creationism, intelligent design, and modern biology -- tChapter 13. The ideological uses of evolutionary biology in recent atheist apologetics -- tAcknowledgments -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aOver the course of human history, the sciences, and biology in particular, have often been manipulated to cause immense human suffering. For example, biology has been used to justify eugenic programs, forced sterilization, human experimentation, and death camps-all in an attempt to support notions of racial superiority. By investigating the past, the contributors to Biology and Ideology from Descartes to Dawkins hope to better prepare us to discern ideological abuse of science when it occurs in the future. Denis R. Alexander and Ronald L. Numbers bring together fourteen experts to examine the varied ways science has been used and abused for nonscientific purposes from the fifteenth century to the present day. Featuring an essay on eugenics from Edward J. Larson and an examination of the progress of evolution by Michael J. Ruse, Biology and Ideology examines uses both benign and sinister, ultimately reminding us that ideological extrapolation continues today. An accessible survey, this collection will enlighten historians of science, their students, practicing scientists, and anyone interested in the relationship between science and culture.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Apr 2021) 0aBiologyxPhilosophy. 0aBiologyxReligious aspects. 0aEugenicsxPhilosophy. 0aEvolution (Biology)xPhilosophy. 0aGeneticsxPhilosophy. 7aSCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aAlexander, Denis R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAlexander, Denis R., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHanns Reill, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHarrison, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKrementsov, Nikolai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLarson, Edward J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLorraine Milam, Erika, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcGrath, Alister E., econtributor.4ctb4http